Then in March, Nigeria shut its air borders, throwing my scheduled return home into disarray. I cried and cried, livid with my husband for not being in Texas with me, for not having enough money to put me up in a hotel.
I wanted to sleep in my own bed in Nigeria, wanted to play with my children back home. I was especially angry with myself. Why did I come to the US? I thought. I had no one here.
Most bothersome was that, the cash I brought was likely to run out. It also didn’t help that the naira had, once again, depreciated against the dollar, meaning, I had to be frugal with expenses.



