Man, I was beyond frustrated. Eventually, I received the correct link to book the flight but couldn’t pay with my card because the bank in Nigeria had imposed an international spending limit of $500 per month.
Nothing seemed to be going right. Eventually, my brother-in-law in Canada paid for the ticket with plans to pay him back in instalments. I was relieved, overjoyed that I was finally going home.
Isolated for two weeks
Save for the health protocols, which passengers had to observe during the flight, the pandemic was a distant event in the back of my mind.
Like most on board the flight, I was preoccupied with getting home with my almost three-month-old baby and reuniting with my family.
When we finally landed in Abuja, officials from the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control informed us before we alighted that we were going to be transported to designated hotels, where we would isolate for two weeks.
We were each given a bag that included a thermometer, a self-regulation book, a hand sanitiser and two face masks. Normal had,indeed, changed. But I was infinitely happy to be back in Nigeria with my baby. Covid-19’s effect on travel has been disastrous. I have learnt that I’m able to handle more than I ever imagined. He was found in a thicket about three kilometres away from Aberdare Country Club. FAO says swarms in Ethiopia, Somalia and Tanzania threaten Kenya’s food security. Nyeri's Serene Haven, which is set to open in January, already has 32 students confirmed to enroll.